Scout: You can still smell the cedar smoke from the kilns. Every roof tile around here was fired three alleys over from mom's workshop.
Scout: Hometown never looks busy from the ridge, but the streets hum before dawn—merchants tuning their bells, kids racing the bakery carts.
Scout: If we keep it safe, the night markets come back. Lanterns on every balcony, and that old brass band on the plaza steps.
